-- Federer Seeded Seventh at U.S. Open, Worst in More Than a Decade
-- B y   R o b   G l o s t e r
-- 2013-08-20T04:01:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-20/federer-seeded-seventh-at-u-s-open-worst-in-more-than-a-decade.html
Roger Federer  will start the U.S.
Open with his worst seeding at a Grand Slam tennis tournament in
more than a decade, falling to seventh on the men’s list.  Novak Djokovic of Serbia, the 2011 U.S. Open champion, will
be the top seed in the last of the tennis season’s four major
tournaments.  Rafael Nadal  of Spain, the 2010 champion, is seeded
second.  Briton  Andy Murray , the reigning champion, is seeded third
and David Ferrer of Spain is fourth in seedings announced
yesterday that followed the world rankings. Tomas Berdych of the
Czech Republic is fifth, followed by 2009 champion Juan Martin Del Potro of Argentina.  Federer, 32, from Switzerland, had been in the top six of
every Grand Slam tournament since he was seeded 13th at the 2002
U.S. Open. He is a five-time U.S. Open winner and has a men’s
record 17 major singles titles.  John Isner , at No. 13, is the only American man among the
top 25 seeds.  The women’s seedings will be announced today. The U.S. Open
is scheduled to run Aug. 26 to Sept. 9 in New York.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Rob Gloster in San Francisco at 
